<span id="freeTextContainer10893979536746689875">I&apos;ve just finished Dumas&apos; &quot;The Count of Monte Cristo&quot; and was curious as to how a modern writer would treat this kind of story. I&apos;ve read two works by Arturo Perez-Reverte (&quot;The Flanders Panel&quot; and &quot;The Fencing Master&quot; and enjoyed both) and in fact the subject of &quot;fencing&quot;, as related in &quot;Monte Cristo/Alatriste&quot; with duels, etc., led me directly to &quot;Captain Alatriste.&quot; I believe this book is the first of at least five more in this series, and it serves a prologue to the rest of the story: here w</span>
  <span id="freeText10893979536746689875" style="display:none">I've just finished Dumas' "The Count of Monte Cristo" and was curious as to how a modern writer would treat this kind of story. I've read two works by Arturo Perez-Reverte ("The Flanders Panel" and "The Fencing Master" and enjoyed both) and in fact the subject of "fencing", as related in "Monte Cristo/Alatriste" with duels, etc., led me directly to "Captain Alatriste." I believe this book is the first of at least five more in this series, and it serves a prologue to the rest of the story: here we have a bit of Alatriste's background, we have mysterious men in mask, we have political intrigue, we have questionable identities. In fact, we have many elements similar to the opening elements of "Monte Cristo". So, today, authors would give us a series of books: if Dumas were publishing today, he would no doubt have given us at lease five volumes of "The Count of Monte Cristo." Times change! And after all, there is far more money to be made in five volumes than just one! Capitalism at its finest. And so far, Alatriste Volume 1 is good enough to keep going!</span>
  <a data-text-id="10893979536746689875" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


